{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17476979","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17476979"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:59+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-28T22:54:59+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14091"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14091","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14091"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.04,0.12,0.04,0.03,0.77]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6759"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52578"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"6759","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/6759"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14091"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37940"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"9"},{"type":"tags","id":"14"},{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1063"},{"type":"tags","id":"7971"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"14739"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35134"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"52578","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/52578"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA two-year-old boy presents to the General Practice clinic with his parent with a three-day history of low-grade fever and a rash. He has no significant medical history and does not take any regular medications. His immunisations are up to date. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears well with vital signs within normal limits. There are small, red, oval-shaped lesions with a grey centre on the soles of his feet (Image). Similar lesions are noted on his palms. He becomes upset and starts screaming, refusing further examination.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely causative agent?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Enterovirus 71","Parvovirus B19","Varicella-zoster virus","Herpes simplex virus","Coxsackievirus A16"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is typical of hand, foot and mouth disease (HFMD), a common childhood illness characterised by fever and vesicular lesions on the hands, feet, and in the oral cavity. The most likely causative agent in this case is \u003Cstrong\u003ECoxsackievirus A16\u003C/strong\u003E, which is responsible for the majority of HFMD cases worldwide.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EEnterovirus 71\u003C/strong\u003E is indeed another important causative agent of HFMD. Both Enterovirus 71 and Coxsackievirus A16 belong to the Enterovirus genus of the Picornaviridae family. Enterovirus 71 is associated with more severe cases and potential neurological complications. However, clinically, it\u0027s not possible to distinguish between these two agents without specific laboratory testing. While Enterovirus 71 is a possible cause, Coxsackievirus A16 remains the most common causative agent of HFMD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHerpes simplex virus\u003C/strong\u003E can cause oral and genital lesions, but typically does not present with the characteristic distribution of lesions seen in HFMD. The lesions caused by herpes simplex are usually more painful and tend to recur in the same location.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EVaricella-zoster virus\u003C/strong\u003E causes chickenpox, which presents with a more widespread, pruritic vesicular rash that appears in crops. It does not have the characteristic distribution of lesions seen in HFMD.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EParvovirus B19\u003C/strong\u003E is responsible for fifth disease (erythema infectiosum), which typically presents with a \u0027slapped cheek\u0027 appearance and a lacy rash on the trunk and extremities, not vesicular lesions on the hands, feet, and mouth.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn this case, the presentation is typical of uncomplicated HFMD, making Coxsackievirus A16 the most likely causative agent. However, it\u0027s important to note that definitive identification of the specific virus would require laboratory testing.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Coxsackievirus A16 is the most common cause of hand, foot and mouth disease.","Enterovirus 71 is another important causative agent of hand, foot and mouth disease.","Hand, foot and mouth disease typically presents with vesicular lesions on the hands, feet, and in the oral cavity."],"references":["Frydenberg A, Starr M. Hand, Foot and Mouth Disease, Australian Family Physician. Available at: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/fe811189-ce71-4a85-b09f-7f49df344e2e/20030805starr2.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37940"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14091"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20983"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20983","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20983"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TIXrXcrF414NkHxtxu09TMwcqFYO6F.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/TIXrXcrF414NkHxtxu09TMwcqFYO6F.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1024,"height":768}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"37940","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/37940"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-09-06T21:15:38+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-05-05T17:19:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"6759"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","